{[%evp 0,39,19,21,18,-36,33,33,39,32,10,10,27,32,41,29,38,-19,25,39,-2,39,78,38,35,44,-6,45,45,28,19,52,-74,53,53,48,80,43,39,22,61,26]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nc3 Nbd7 7. O-O e5 8. e4 (8. Qc2 $6 exd4 9. Nxd4 Nb6 $1 {[%cal Gc7c5]}) 8... c6 9. Qc2 {The plan is straightforward: we're preparing Rd1, and if Black isn't careful, d5 could follow.} exd4 {is Black's best try. He should generally open the position and play around the dark squares, like c5 and e5.} (9... Re8 10. Rd1 Qe7 11. d5 $1 a5 (11... c5 12. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4]} Rf8 13. b4 Ne8 14. Rb1 Nc7 15. Bg5 Qe8 16. Nh4 {is a typical move, fighting against the ...f5 break!} a5 17. bxa5 Rxa5 18. Rb3 $16 {[%csl Rb7] Inarkiev,E (2591)-Gutman,G (2509) Pardubice 2004}) 12. Be3 Ng4 13. Bg5 f6 14. Bc1 Nc5 15. h3 Nh6 16. Be3 Nf7 17. Qd2 Qf8 {[%cal Gg7h6,Gf6f5]} 18. Nh2 {[%cal Gd1f1,Gf2f4,Ga1d1] Due to Black's passive play, we can now switch sides and start playing on the kingside, simply preparing f4 ourselves!} Kh8 (18... f5 19. exf5 {[%csl Rc6]} gxf5 20. dxc6 $18) (18... Bh6 19. f4 $16 {[%cal Gd2f2,Gd1e1,Ga1d1]}) (18... Rd8 19. Rf1 $16 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) 19. Rf1 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ga1d1] /}) 10. Nxd4 Re8 {Black will have to play this move at some point.} (10... Nc5 11. Bf4 $1 Ng4 12. Rad1 Ne5 13. b3 a5 14. h3 $16 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd1d2,Yg1h2,Gf4e3] We will slowly prepare f4, while the d6 pawn remains our long-term target.}) (10... Qb6 11. Nde2 $1 Ne5 12. b3 $16 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gc1a3,Ga1d1] We stabilize the position and structure. The plan is Ba3 followed by Rad1, putting pressure on d6.}) (10... Nb6 {is played by a few players aiming to implement the ...d5 break with tempo.} 11. b3 d5 12. Ba3 $1 (12. exd5 $1 Nfxd5 13. cxd5 Bxd4 14. Bh6 Bf5 15. Qd2 Bg7 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Qd4+ Qf6 18. Qxf6+ Kxf6 19. dxc6 bxc6 20. Rac1 Rac8 21. Rfd1 $14 {[%csl Ya7,Yc6]}) 12... Nxe4 {Sygulski,A (2425)-Uhlmann,W (2470) Potsdam 1985} (12... Re8 $6 {Ermenkov,E (2475)-Ristic,N (2440) Groningen 1988} 13. exd5 cxd5 14. c5 Nbd7 15. Ndb5 $18 {[%cal Gb5d6]}) 13. Bxf8 Bxd4 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. Bh6 $14 {[%cal Gh6e3,Gc3e4]}) 11. Rd1 {Now we target the d6 pawn, with Bf4 coming next.} Qe7 12. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Rd6]} Ne5 {The most natural move: neutralize pressure on d6, attack the c4 pawn, and prepare ...a6 followed by ...b5.} (12... Nh5 $6 13. Be3 a5 14. h3 Nc5 (14... Nhf6 {Jumabayev,R (2646)-Demchenko,A (2642) Moscow RUS 2019} 15. Re1 $1 Nc5 16. Rad1 $16 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg3g4] Once we achieve f4, we will have an ideal setup against this structure.}) 15. Re1 $1 (15. Nb3 f5 $1 $132 {Yoo,C (2607)-Sasikiran,K (2604) chess.com INT 2023}) 15... a4 16. Rad1 Be6 17. b4 axb3 18. axb3 $16 {[%csl Rd6,Yh5][%cal Gg3g4,Gb3b4,Ye1e2,Ye2d2,Gd4f5] Black's pieces are misplaced, and we will continue naturally with g4/b4, while Nf5 is always in the air, exploiting the queen's poor placement on e7. According to the engine, we have a pleasant +1.20 advantage.}) 13. b3 a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} (13... Nh5 14. Be3 Qf8 $5 {[%cal Gf7f5] An interesting attempt to prepare ...f5.} (14... Ng4 $6 15. Bc1 $1 f5 $2 {An aggressive attempt, but we simply neutralize with Zhidkov,V (2315)-Belozerov,A (2325) Moscow 1995} 16. h3 $1 {[%csl Rf5,Rg4]} Nh6 (16... Bxd4 $2 17. Rxd4 Ne5 18. exf5 Bxf5 19. Qd1 $18 {[%csl Rd6,Rf5,Rh5][%cal Gg3g4,Gd4d6,Gc3e4]}) (16... fxe4 17. hxg4 Bxg4 18. Be3 Bxd1 19. Rxd1 $18 {[%csl Re4][%cal Yh5f6,Ye3g5];1-0 Harikrishnan,A (2448)-Kotronias,V (2448) Budapest FS03 GM-2 2024 (2)}) 17. Bxh6 Bxh6 18. exf5 $18 {[%cal Gc3e4]}) 15. Rab1 $1 a6 (15... f5 16. exf5 gxf5 17. Nce2 $16 {[%csl Rd6,Yf5,Yh7][%cal Ge2f4] After all, there's no attack, and Black is left with a damaged structure. The endgame will be difficult for him.}) (15... Ng4 16. Bc1 f5 17. h3 Ne5 18. exf5 gxf5 19. f4 $16) 16. h3 f5 17. exf5 Bxf5 (17... gxf5 {[%cal Gf5f4]} 18. Bc1 Bd7 19. Qe2 (19. Nce2 c5 20. Nf3 Bc6 21. Nh4 Ng6 22. Bxc6 bxc6 23. Nxg6 hxg6 24. Kg2 $14 {[%csl Ya6,Rd6][%cal Gc2d3,Gc1g5] /}) 19... Qf7 (19... Nf6 20. f4 Ng6 21. Qc2 $16 {[%csl Rf5]}) 20. Nd5 $1 Rab8 21. Bg5 h6 22. Be3 Rbd8 23. Rbc1 $14 {/}) 18. Nxf5 gxf5 19. Ne2 Ng6 20. Qd2 $14 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gd1e1,Gg2f3,Ya8d8,Ye3g5]}) (13... Nfd7 14. h3 Nc5 {[%cal Gc5e6]} 15. Be3 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ge3f2] This would be our dream position because after f4 and Bf2, we achieve the ideal setup in this structure.}) 14. h3 b5 (14... Rb8 {Preparing ...c5, followed by ...b5.} 15. Qd2 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd4f3]} c5 16. Nf3 $1 {A slight improvement over the Grachev game. While 16.Nde2 is also a good move, I believe Nf3 is stronger, as it directly threats Nxe5 and Bg5.} (16. Nde2 b5 17. cxb5 axb5 18. Qxd6 Qxd6 19. Rxd6 b4 20. Na4 Nh5 21. Rad1 $16 {Grachev,B (2621)-Belozerov,A (2533) Yaroslavl RUS 2019}) 16... Nh5 (16... b5 $2 17. Nxe5 dxe5 18. Bg5 {[%csl Re7][%cal Gc3d5]} Be6 (18... Qf8 19. cxb5 axb5 20. a4 $18) 19. Nd5 Bxd5 20. cxd5 $18 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ga1c1,Gg5e3]}) 17. Nd5 Qd8 18. Bg5 Nxf3+ 19. Bxf3 Nf6 20. Nxf6+ Bxf6 21. Bxf6 Qxf6 22. Qxd6 Qxd6 23. Rxd6 Bxh3 24. g4 {[%csl Rh3]} h5 25. gxh5 $18 {[%csl Rc5,Rh5][%cal Gd6d5] Being a pawn up in this endgame, with bishops of the same color, I believe we have a decisive advantage.}) 15. c5 $1 {It’s a basic element of White's strategy in the Fianchetto KID. When executed under the right circumstances, it removes the d6 pawn, activates the pawn structure with f4-e5, opens the light-squared bishop, and leaves Black's queenside weakened.} dxc5 16. Bxe5 cxd4 (16... Qxe5 $2 {allows us to open the position with} 17. Nxc6 {leading to an endgame with a pawn up and a decisive advantage.} Qc7 18. e5 $1 Bf5 19. Qc1 b4 20. exf6 bxc3 21. Qxc3 Be4 22. Qxc5 Bxf6 23. Rac1 Bxg2 24. Kxg2 $18 {[%cal Gc5d5,Gd5d7]}) 17. Bxd4 Bb7 ({One of the top KID experts played} 17... Be6 $6 {Liu,Y (2476)-Kotronias,V (2529) Moscow RUS 2018} {here, but I propose} 18. Ne2 $1 Rad8 19. Rac1 $16 {[%csl Ya6,Yb5,Yc6][%cal Gd4c5,Gf2f4] where Black's queenside weakness is clear. Meanwhile, we also threat Bc5 and f4.}) 18. Rac1 $1 {[%csl Ga5,Gb6,Yb7,Gc5] We are fighting for control of all the dark squares.} (18. e5 Nh5 19. Ne4 c5 $1 20. Nf6+ Nxf6 21. exf6 Qc7 22. Bxb7 Qxb7 23. Qxc5 Bf8 $132 {[%cal Gb7f3,Gh7h5]}) 18... Nh5 ({Black can try to activate his bishop with} 18... c5 $5 {but after} 19. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 20. Bxc5 {[%csl Rd5,Re7]} Nb4 21. Qd2 Qe6 22. Qxb4 $16 {we won a pawn and gain a dominant position.}) 19. Bb6 {[%cal Ra8d8]} Rac8 (19... Bh6 20. Rb1 {[%cal Gb3b4]} a5 {is the most logical move, since Black must prevent b4.} (20... Rac8 21. b4 $1 $16 {[%csl Ya6,Yb5,Rb7,Yc6] would completely shut down the queenside.}) 21. Re1 $14 {[%csl Yb7,Yh5,Yh6][%cal Gb1d1,Ge4e5,Gf2f4] /. With Rad1 coming, followed by f4-e5, and Black's pieces miscoordinated, we have a position that's more than just pleasant.}) 20. Qd2 $14 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gd2d7,Gf2f4,Ge4e5] I think we can stop here. We control the d-file and threat Qd7. The f4-e5 is coming, achieving the perfect structure and shutting down the bishop on g7. Meanwhile, Black's queenside and the bishop on b7 are under control, with the bishop on b6 doing a great job.} *

