{[%evp 39,39,31]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nc3 Nbd7 7. O-O e5 8. e4 exd4 9. Nxd4 Re8 {While 10.h3 Nc5 11.Re1 remains the most popular line, I prefer} 10. Be3 $5 {followed by f3. The idea is simple: we want to play Bf2-h3 and, at the right moment, push f4 to reach the ideal setup for White against this structure.} Nc5 11. f3 c6 12. Qc2 $1 a5 13. Rad1 Nfd7 (13... Qe7 $6 {is misplaced here; Black should go for the more active plan with a4 followed by Qa5.} 14. Rfe1 h5 15. h3 Bd7 16. Bf4 Bf8 {1-0 Myshkin,N (2311)-Radovanovic,N (2408) BL2-Ost 1920 Germany 2019 (1.8)}) 14. Bf2 $1 a4 $1 {Black's plan is to establish a strong square on a5 for the queen.} (14... Ne5 15. b3 $1 (15. f4 $5 {could also be interesting, as it's not clear what is happening on the board.} Nxc4 16. b3 Nb6 17. Nxc6 $5 bxc6 18. Bxc5 Nd5 $1 19. exd5 Bf5 20. Qc1 dxc5 21. dxc6 Bd4+ 22. Kh1 {[%cal Gc3d5]} Qf6 23. Nd5 Qd6 24. Qc4 Rac8 25. c7 $13 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gb3b4]}) 15... a4 $1 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gb6a5]} ({Strangely, all three players in the database played the suspicious} 15... Qf6 $2 {after which} 16. h3 $1 {makes it impossible to prevent 17.f4.} Qe7 (16... h5 17. f4 Ned7 18. Qd2 $16 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gf1e1,Gg1h2] I don't see any counterplay for Black.}) 17. f4 Ned7 18. Rfe1 Nf8 {1-0 Razuvaev,Y (2580)-Esaibekian,M (2135) Yerevan op 1996 (1)} 19. g4 $18 {[%csl Ge4,Gf2,Gf4,Gg2,Gg4] An ideal setup for White. Black has no counterplay and no clear plan, leaving us with a strategically winning position.}) 16. h3 $1 Qb6 17. f4 Ned7 18. Rb1 (18. Ndb5 $5 axb3 19. axb3 cxb5 20. Nxb5 {[%cal Gb3b4]} Qa5 21. Nxd6 Rd8 22. e5 $13) 18... axb3 19. axb3 Qb4 20. g4 Ra3 21. Nce2 Nf8 (21... Nf6 22. Ng3 $1 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gd4b5]} Qb6 {Avoiding the threat of 23.Nb5!} (22... Bxg4 23. Nb5 $1 {[%csl Ra3,Rb4][%cal Gf2e1]}) 23. g5 Nfd7 24. Rfd1 $16 {[%cal Gh3h4]}) 22. Kh1 {preparing Nb5 followed by Be1, aiming to trap the queen on b4.} (22. Nb5 $5 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gf2e1]} Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Rf2e1,Rb4c5] Here, we see the benefit of 22.Kh1, avoiding ...Qc5+.} 23. Nxa3 Nxf2 24. Rxf2 Qxa3 25. Qd2 $14 {[%cal Gg2f3,Gg1g2]}) 22... Nce6 $1 {A precise move, as 23.Nfe6 would allow 23.Nb5!} (22... Nfe6 23. Nb5 $1 cxb5 24. Be1 {[%csl Rb4]} Qxb3 25. Rxb3 Rxb3 26. e5 $1 $36 {[%cal Ge2c1,Yf4f5,Ye2d4]}) 23. f5 Nxd4 24. Nxd4 Nd7 25. Rbd1 $14 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gf2e1,Ge1c3,Yd4f3] Our next idea is to transfer the bishop to c3, followed by Nf3, putting pressure on the d6 pawn. White enjoys a small but long-lasting advantage.}) 15. Rfe1 Qa5 16. h3 {Covering the g4 square and slowly preparing f4.} Ne5 {1-0 Goryachkina,A (2545)-Lopez del Alamo,A (2237) Titled Tuesday intern op 28th May Early Chess.com INT blitz 2024 (2)} (16... Nb6 $146 17. Nce2 Qb4 18. Rc1 $14 {[%cal Ge1d1,Gg1h2,Yf3f4] With the same ideas as in the main line.}) 17. Nce2 $1 {At first, 17.Nce2 may seem unusual, but it is definitely preferable. First, we avoid 17.b3, where after 17...axb3 18.axb3, Black would create counterplay around the pawn, which would become a long-term weakness. The second benefit of 17.Nce2 is that after f4-g4, we can transfer the knight to g3, as seen in the 14...Ne5 line.} Qa6 ({The standard idea} 17... Qb4 $6 {doesn't work here, as we have} 18. f4 $1 {with the pawn on c4 indirectly defended.} Nxc4 $6 19. a3 $16 {[%csl Rb4,Rc4]}) (17... Bd7 {is also possible.} 18. b3 $1 ({It's important not to rush with} 18. f4 $6 {where Black could sacrifice a piece for activity.} Nxc4 19. Qxc4 Nxe4 20. Bxe4 Rxe4 $132 {[%cal Ga8e8,Gd7h3]}) 18... axb3 19. axb3 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf3f4] Now it's clear that the best move is to retreat the bishop, allowing the knight to have a safe square on d7.} Bc8 20. f4 Ned7 21. g4 $14 {[%cal Ge2g3,Yf4f5] We have reached a position rich with ideas, from which we can build up with various plans. Ng3-f5 is one idea, as well as Rf1 preparing Be1-Bc3. In general, I think it's much easier to play for White, as Black is the one who needs to find good counterplay.}) 18. b3 $14 {[%cal Gg1h2,Gf3f4] The right moment for this move. Our next moves will be f4-g4, followed by Bg3 or Rd2-Red1, depending on how Black responds.According to the engine, we have a pleasant +0.45 advantage.} (18. b4 Qxc4 $5 19. bxc5 dxc5 20. Qxc4 Nxc4 21. Nc2 Nb2 $132 {[%cal Gb2d3]}) *

