{[%evp 0,43,17,31,9,16,28,24,46,16,2,11,30,31,40,39,39,30,35,40,40,-11,9,38,44,46,70,148,59,70,49,30,50,30,43,207,74,76,47,65,69,63,88,168,49,47]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nc3 Nbd7 7. O-O e5 8. e4 c6 9. Qc2 Qe7 (9... Qc7 $6 {The queen doesn't belong on c7 in this type of structure. It would be much better placed on a more active square, like e7, where it contributes to the position more effectively.} 10. Rd1 Re8 11. h3 {It's always useful to control the g4 square, ensuring that Be3 can be played without having to deal with ...Ng4 ideas.} exd4 (11... a5 $6 {would be premature here since after} 12. Be3 $1 exd4 {we have the strong novelty} 13. Rxd4 $1 $146 {targeting the d6 pawn.} Nc5 14. Rad1 {[%csl Rd6]} a4 15. Nh2 $1 {[%csl Rd6,Ge4] A strong move! Defending the e4 pawn, threatening Rxd6, and preparing f4.} Re6 16. R4d2 h5 17. Bd4 $16 {[%csl Ya8,Yc8][%cal Gf2f4]}) 12. Nxd4 Nc5 13. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Rd6] I've always loved this typical move. White can play 13.Be3, but with 13.Bf4, we put strong pressure on the d6 pawn and provoke ...Nh5, forcing the knight into an awkward position before returning to e3.} Nh5 14. Be3 {[%csl Yh5]} a5 ({Of course, Black can return with} 14... Nf6 {but we've gained a tempo and can quickly regroup our pieces to better squares.} 15. Re1 $1 a5 16. b3 $1 {[%cal Ra5a4]} (16. Rad1 a4 $1 {[%csl Ya2,Yb2]}) 16... Bd7 (16... Nfd7 17. Kh2 $5 {A prophylactic move: we move the king off the potential danger along the g1-a7 diagonal, allowing f4 to be played safely.} b6 (17... Ne5 $6 {0-1 Khromkin,A (2191)-Jia,H (2331) Titled Tuesday intern op 08th Aug Early Chess.com INT blitz 2023 (3) doesn't make sense here, as} 18. Rad1 {covers the d3 square, and f4 is coming with tempo.} h5 19. f4 Ned7 20. Qd2 $18 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd4c2,Ge3d4] After Nc2, Black will have difficulties defending the d6 pawn.}) 18. Rad1 Bb7 19. Re2 $16 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ge2d2,Gd4e2] Our pieces are ideally placed, and we're ready to create a battery on the d-file. After that, we can play Nde2 followed by f4, establishing a dominant structure.})) 15. Nb3 $1 $146 {According to the engine, this novelty secures a much larger advantage for us compared to 15.Rd2.} ({Of course, there's nothing wrong with} 15. Rd2 {once again preparing a battery on the d-file. After Nde2, we put pressure on the d6 pawn and prepare f4 at the right moment.} a4 16. Rad1 Qa5 17. Nde2 $14) 15... f5 16. Nxc5 f4 $1 17. Na6 $1 Rxa6 18. gxf4 Qe7 19. Ne2 a4 20. Ng3 Nxg3 21. fxg3 a3 22. Bd4 Bxd4+ 23. Rxd4 axb2 24. Qxb2 Be6 25. Qc3 $16 {A pawn up with same-colored bishops gives us a more pleasant endgame. Black can try some counterplay on the a2 pawn, but he also faces the issue of the d6 pawn. Our king is much safer than Black's, and exchanging the a2 pawn for the d6 pawn would leave us with a 4 vs 2 majority on the kingside, where Black's king is already exposed.}) 10. Re1 $5 (10. b3 exd4 11. Nxd4 Nxe4 $1) 10... exd4 $1 (10... Re8 $6 {Definitely not the right move for Black. Now, we have time for everything.} 11. h3 $1 {[%cal Rf6g4]} a6 (11... b6 12. Bg5 Bb7 13. Rad1 $16 {[%cal Gd4d5]}) 12. d5 $1 $146 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gb2b4] }) 11. Nxd4 Ng4 12. Rd1 $1 (12. Nce2 $5 Nc5 {½-½ Raupp,T (2370)-Schaefer,M (2460) Bundesliga 9394 Germany 1993 (10.5)} 13. Bd2 Ne5 14. Rf1 $14 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gb2b3]}) 12... Nc5 13. h3 Ne5 14. b3 f5 $1 {The most energetic response from Black; otherwise, after 15.f4, we would regroup our pieces just in time and achieve a perfect setup.} 15. f4 Nf7 $1 16. exf5 Bxd4+ {Here starts the forcing line, leading to a slightly better endgame where Black will definitely face problems due to the absence of his dark-squared bishop.} 17. Rxd4 Qe1+ 18. Kh2 Bxf5 19. Qd2 Qxd2 20. Rxd2 {[%cal Gg3g4]} h5 $1 {[%cal Rg3g4]} (20... Rae8 $2 {shows how easy it is to make a mistake and how important it is for Black to play 20...h5!} 21. g4 $1 Ne4 22. Bxe4 $1 Bxe4 23. Re2 Bd3 24. Re3 Bc2 (24... Rxe3 25. Bxe3 Re8 26. Bf2 $1 $16 {[%csl Rd6,Yf7][%cal Ga1d1,Gh2g3]} ({There's nothing wrong with} 26. Bxa7 $1 c5 27. Rd1 Re3 28. Nd5 Re2+ 29. Kg3 Bc2 30. Rf1 $16 {[%cal Gf1f2]}))) 21. Ba3 $1 Rae8 22. Rf1 $14 {[%csl Ga3,Yd6,Gg2][%cal Gf1f2,Gg2f3] The bishop pair and the weak d6 pawn definitely secure White a slightly better position. According to the engine, Black's position is solid, but practically speaking, I believe White's position remains preferable.} *

