{[%evp 0,31,12,0,25,17,34,39,34,10,11,7,23,32,27,9,32,29,46,31,32,41,35,33,51,38,43,43,50,44,54,47,50,39]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nc3 Nbd7 7. O-O e5 8. e4 a6 {Obviously, Black's idea is to prepare ...b5.} (8... h6 $5 {[%cal Gf6h7,Gh7g5] This interesting line has been played by many King's Indian experts, including Grivas, Miles, and Markus. Black's idea is to play Nh7-Ng5. However, White has a simple way to claim a dominant position.} 9. Qc2 $1 Nh7 10. Be3 Ng5 11. Rad1 Nxf3+ (11... Re8 12. Nxg5 hxg5 13. f3 a5 14. Qf2 exd4 15. Bxd4 $16 {[%cal Gf3f4] White has a dominant position.}) 12. Bxf3 exd4 {The most logical move.} 13. Bxd4 Bxd4 14. Rxd4 Qf6 15. Qd1 $1 Ne5 16. Bg2 {and we have an amazing structure. The game can continue with} Bg4 17. f3 Be6 18. Nd5 Bxd5 19. cxd5 $16 {[%csl Rc7] where our bishop dominates the knight, especially with the pressure on the c7 pawn along the c-file.}) 9. Qe2 $5 {Played only once in a correspondence game. Placing the queen on e2 is not natural, but it stops ...b5 and also prepares Rd1.} ({According to the engine, the best move is} 9. Qc2 {but I would like to show some other ideas in this structure.} exd4 10. Nxd4 Ne5 11. b3 c5 12. Nde2 Rb8 13. a4 $14) 9... exd4 {seems to be the most logical move since, after ...Re8, Black will put pressure along the e-file.} (9... b5 $6 {would be premature, as after} 10. dxe5 $1 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. Rd1 Qe7 13. cxb5 axb5 14. Qxb5 $16 {we win a full pawn with no compensation for Black.}) 10. Nxd4 Re8 {[%cal Re8e2]} 11. Rd1 Rb8 {1-0 Zinoviev,P (2235)-Bobel,P (2302) FRA AJEC 80jub sf06 email ICCF email 2018} (11... Qe7 12. Bf4 (12. h3 {looks like a good alternative line.} Nc5 13. Bg5 {[%cal Gc3d5]} c6 (13... h6 $2 14. Nd5 Qd8 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Bxh6 $16) 14. Qd2 {[%cal Rh7h6]} Qf8 15. Qc2 a5 16. Rd2 $14 {[%csl Yd6][%cal Gg5e3,Ga1d1]}) 12... Nc5 13. Re1 Qf8 14. Qd2 h6 15. f3 $14 {[%cal Gf4e3,Ga1d1] We will continue with Rad1 and Be3, pressing forward with a better structure and space advantage.}) (11... c6 {[%cal Gd6d5] is also an interesting idea. Black aims to play ...d5, exploiting the queen's position on e2.} 12. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Rd6] will help us achieve e5, leaving Black with an isolated pawn on d5.} d5 13. cxd5 Nxd5 $1 (13... cxd5 $2 {would allow us to win the pawn after} 14. e5 $1 {[%cal Yd7b6,Ya2a4]} Nh5 15. Nf3 Nxf4 16. gxf4 Nb6 17. a4 $16 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf3g5]}) 14. Nxd5 cxd5 15. Nb3 $1 Nf6 16. e5 Bf5 17. h3 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gg3g4] /. The pawn on d5 will be lost very soon. To save the game, Black will need to find quick and strong counterplay.}) 12. Bg5 $5 {As strong as 12.Be3 or 12.Bf4 are, I prefer to first provoke ...h6 before returning to e3. We can always play Qd2 with tempo.} (12. Be3 c5 13. Nb3 Qe7 14. h3 b6 15. Re1 Bb7 16. Rad1 $14) (12. Bf4 Nc5 (12... c5 $2 13. Nf3 $18 {[%csl Rd6]}) 13. f3 Ne6 14. Nxe6 Bxe6 15. Rac1 $14) 12... h6 13. Be3 Qe7 14. h3 Nc5 15. f3 Ne6 16. Rac1 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4] We will continue with b4 and Nb3, gradually improving our position. Of course, our goal is to play f4 at the right moment, but there's no need to rush. It's on Black to find good counterplay while we control the center and enjoy a space advantage. We have a promising position full of ideas, while Black remains solid.} *

