{[%evp 0,35,14,29,19,19,32,37,42,15,7,16,38,32,38,35,39,30,45,12,41,79,56,57,74,124,62,50,65,81,-51,43,65,70,64,65,1,58]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nc3 Nbd7 7. O-O e5 8. e4 b6 (8... Re8 9. h3 {It's always good to control the g4 square in this type of structure.} b6 10. Qc2 exd4 (10... Bb7 $6 11. d5 $1 {Now, with Bb7 and Rfe8 played, it's the right moment for this move. The bishop remains restricted on b7, while the rook on e8 can't support the ...f7-f5 idea.} a5 {[%cal Gd7c5]} 12. Be3 {[%cal Rf6g4] Here we can see the benefit of 9.h3.} Nc5 13. Rfe1 {[%csl Ge4] It can be useful to defend the e4 pawn in the future.} Bc8 {[%cal Gc8d7] It's time to bring the bishop back to life, as on b7 it doesn't do anything useful.} 14. a3 $1 {We usually start with b3, then a3, slowly preparing b4. But here, 14...a4 is not possible, as we can simply capture the knight on c5 and the pawn on a4.} Bd7 (14... a4 $6 {[%csl Ya3,Ga4,Yb2]} 15. Bxc5 bxc5 16. Nxa4 $16 {[%csl Ge1,Ge4]}) 15. b4 $16 {Strategically speaking, I think White has a dominant position. Black hasn't initiated any play on the kingside, while we have already made significant progress on the queenside.}) 11. Nxd4 Bb7 12. Bg5 $5 {With the idea of provoking ...h6, there will be a moment when the ...d5 break is not possible, as we have the in-between Bxh6!"} (12. Be3 Nc5 13. f3 d5 14. cxd5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Rad1 {is also a good line for White.}) 12... h6 (12... Nc5 13. Rad1 {[%cal Gc3d5]} h6 14. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 (14... Qxf6 $2 {allows us to win material by force, leading to a dominant endgame.} 15. e5 $1 {[%csl Rb7,Rf6]} Qxe5 16. Bxb7 Nxb7 17. Nd5 {[%csl Rc7]} Rac8 18. Nc6 Qxb2 19. Nde7+ Kf8 20. Qxb2 Bxb2 21. Nxc8 Rxc8 22. Nxa7 Ra8 23. Nb5 $16 {[%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e2,Gg1g2,Gh3h4] /+-}) 15. f4 $1 Bg7 16. e5 dxe5 17. Nc6 Qc8 18. fxe5 Re6 $1 19. Rd8+ Qxd8 20. Nxd8 Rxd8 21. Nd5 Rxe5 22. b4 $14 {[%cal Gf1d1]}) 13. Be3 a6 $146 {[%cal Gc7c5] A novelty, and probably the best continuation for Black, simply preparing ...c5.} (13... Nc5 14. f3 c6 {Barbot,P (2460)-Popovic,D (2498) Veli Losinj CRO 2023} (14... d5 $2 {Now, typical ..d5 doesn't work because after} 15. cxd5 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. Rad1 Qe7 (17... Qf6 18. b4 Na6 19. a3 {[%csl Ra6]} c5 20. Nb5 $16 {[%cal Gb4c5,Gb5d6]}) {we have} 18. Bxh6 {Here, we see the benefit of 12.Bg5, provoking 12...h6.} Bxh6 19. exd5 $16) 15. Rad1 Rc8 $146 {[%cal Gd6d5]} (15... Qc7 $6 {0-1 Konopka,M (2381)-Plischki,S (2368) CZE-chT 2122 Czech Republic 2021 (8.1)} 16. Bf2 $1 $16 {[%cal Gf3f4] would lead to a perfect setup for White.}) (15... d5 $146 16. b4 $1 Na6 17. b5 cxb5 18. cxb5 Nc7 (18... Nc5 19. Nc6 Bxc6 20. bxc6 $18 {[%csl Rd5]}) 19. Bf2 $14 {[%cal Gd4c6,Gf3f4] White definitely has a promising position.}) 16. Nb3 Nxb3 17. Qxb3 $14 {[%csl Yb7,Rd6][%cal Gf1e1,Ge3f2]}) 14. Rad1 c5 15. Nb3 (15. Nde2 {leads to complex, unclear positions.} Qe7 16. Nf4 g5 17. Nfd5 Nxd5 18. cxd5 b5 19. f4 b4 20. Na4 gxf4 21. gxf4 Kh8 22. e5 $13 {[%cal Gg1h1,Gc2f5]}) 15... Ne5 16. Nd2 $13 {[%cal Gf1e1,Gc3d5,Gf2f4] We'll continue with Rfe1, followed by f4 at the right moment. Black's Nc6-Nd4 could be an option, but we can always kick the knight with Nb3. Overall, the modern ...b6 variation gives Black a solid position, but White's play remains easier.}) 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. dxe5 $1 {I believe this is an important improvement over 10.d5. The structure is definitely favorable, as ...c6 is no longer possible, leaving us with a strong outpost on d6 and restricting the bishop on b7. Nd5 could always be a strong threat.} dxe5 11. Rd1 Qb8 $5 {A strange-looking move, but it works. Now, 12.Nd5 doesn't pose any threat to Black, as c7 is defended.} (11... Qe7 {would allow us to play} 12. Nd5 $1 {where after} Nxd5 13. cxd5 {[%csl Rb7,Rc7] we can organize our play on the c-file, putting pressure on the c7 pawn, while the bishop on b7 remains restricted.} c6 $1 (13... Qc5 14. Qa4 $1 Qd6 15. Be3 $16 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Ga1c1]}) 14. Bg5 Nf6 15. d6 Qe6 16. Qb3 $1 $16 {[%csl Rb7,Gd6]}) (11... Qe8 {would leave the c7 pawn hard to defend.} 12. Nd5 $1 Rc8 13. Bh3 $1 $16 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Rh3c8]}) 12. Be3 Re8 13. b4 $1 {A typical move, we are gaining space on the queenside.} c6 (13... Bf8 $5 14. a3 a5 15. Rab1 {[%cal Gg2h3]} c6 {[%cal Gb8c7]} 16. h3 $14 {[%cal Gf3e1,Ge1d3] /. Black's position seems very passive, with little to no counterplay. The pieces are poorly coordinated, and Black's lack of activity leaves him vulnerable to White's plans. White has complete control of key squares, and the lack of space for Black's pieces to maneuver further highlights the passive nature of the position.}) 14. c5 $1 {[%csl Rb7] Restricting the bishop on b7 while also preventing any ...a5 counterplay.} bxc5 15. bxc5 Bf8 {[%csl Rc5]} 16. Na4 {[%csl Ya7,Gc5,Yc6]} Ba6 17. Bh3 $1 {[%csl Rd7]} Qc7 18. Rd2 $1 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Ga1d1] We will continue to apply pressure on the d-file with Rad1. I love how White's pieces are harmoniously placed, while it's unclear what Black's plan will be. According to the engine, the evaluation is +0.65.} *

