{[%evp 0,39,12,13,7,21,44,33,27,16,8,13,34,41,40,34,33,12,31,24,37,36,26,21,21,5,-7,18,50,6,-47,41,43,-11,-89,65,58,35,68,73,71,-8]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nc3 $1 {With this move order, we avoid dozens of different lines that Black could use if we chose to castle first.} (6. O-O Nc6 7. Nc3 {[%cal Ga7a6,Ga8b8,Gc8g4,Ge7e5,Gc8f5]}) 6... Nc6 7. d5 Na5 8. b3 c5 9. Bb2 a6 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gb7b5]} 10. Nd2 Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5]} (10... Bd7 {is a reasonable move, but if Black later plays ...e6 or ...e5, he will lose a tempo.} 11. O-O (11. Qc2 {is also possible, but I prefer to stick with our idea of Qc1.} Rb8 (11... b5 12. Nce4 Nxe4 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Bxe4 $14 {[%cal Gc2c3,Gh2h4] /}) 12. Nce4 Nxe4 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Nxe4 b5 15. O-O $14 {[%csl Ra5]}) 11... b5 12. Qc1 Rb8 13. Rb1 Qc7 (13... Qc8 $6 {[%cal Gd7h3]} 14. Nd1 (14. Qc2 {is also possible, but the idea remains the same: e4 followed by Ne3-f4.} Bh3 15. Nd1 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 e5 17. e4 Qd7 18. Ne3 $16 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) 14... Bh3 15. e4 {[%cal Gd1e3]} Bxg2 16. Kxg2 e5 17. Ne3 Ng4 18. Nxg4 Qxg4 19. f3 Qd7 {1-0 Olsen,F (2423)-Rudd,J (2314) London GM-B 2023 (3)} 20. f4 $1 $16 {[%csl Ra5]}) (13... e5 {doesn't make much sense, especially since Black already played ...Bd7, but it's still a possible move. After} 14. dxe6 Bxe6 15. cxb5 axb5 16. Nde4 Nxe4 17. Nxe4 Bf5 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Qc3+ f6 20. Rbd1 {[%csl Rd6]} Bxe4 21. Bxe4 $14 {[%csl Ya5,Rd6,Ge4][%cal Gd1d2,Gf1d1,Gh2h4] we remain with the better bishop compared to Black's knight and the d6 weakness. According to the engine, White is slightly better.}) 14. Nd1 $1 {A standard plan in this type of structure. White is preparing e4 and Ne3.} e5 {1-0 Fressinet,L (2632)-Giroyan,G (2428) FRA-ch Rapid Asnieres sur Seine 2023 (4)} 15. e4 bxc4 16. bxc4 Bh6 17. f4 $14 {/}) 11. O-O b5 12. Qc1 $1 {I prefer 12.Qc1 because, in many lines after the ...e5 break, the sequence dxe6 fxe6 makes Nce4 more effective. In this case, Black gains no benefit from playing ...Bf5, as the Queen would not be pinned. By playing 12.Qc1, we avoid this counterplay from the opponent, and the Queen can quickly shift to the kingside with Qh6, supporting the attack on the kingside, as seen in the game Krysa - Moehn.} bxc4 $6 (12... e6 13. dxe6 Bxe6 14. cxb5 $1 axb5 15. Nce4 $1 {[%cal Re6f5] Now the idea behind 12.Qc1 is clear: Black can't pin us with 15...Bf5} Ne8 (15... Nxe4 $2 16. Nxe4 Bf5 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Qc3+ f6 19. Nxd6 Qxd6 20. Qxa5 $16) (15... Nd5 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Qb2+ f6 18. Rfd1 $16 {[%csl Ra5,Rd6][%cal Gd2f1]}) (15... Bf5 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. h3 $1 {[%cal Gg3g4,Gd2e4]} (17. g4 $5 $146 {Interesting move I played against my FM student in a training game. After} Bxg4 18. Ne4 Bxb2 19. Qxb2 {he played} f6 {where after} (19... f5 {seems like a better move, after which} 20. Ng3 Qf6 21. Qd2 {[%csl Ra5]} f4 22. Ne4 Qd8 23. Rfd1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ga2a4] leaves us with a slightly better position.}) 20. Rfd1 Nb7 21. a4 {[%csl Ga4,Rd6] I believe we have a dominant position.}) 17... h5 18. e4 Bd7 19. e5 $1 dxe5 20. Ne4 Bg7 {1-0 Espinosa Aranda,A (2449)-Jing,A (2177) Villablanca Bambuchess 4th 2024 (6)} 21. Qxc5 $1 Rc8 22. Qe3 $1 {[%cal Gf1d1,Ge4d6] We will continue with Rfd1, followed by Nd6. According to the engine, the evaluation is +0.40.}) 16. Bxg7 Nxg7 17. Nf3 $16 Bf5 $2 18. Qh6 {[%cal Gf3g5]} g5 19. Nf6+ Kh8 20. Nxh7 {1-0 Krysa,L (2542)-Moehn,H (2382) Spilimbergo ITA 2023}) (12... e5 13. dxe6 Bxe6 {is same as 12...e6.}) (12... Re8 13. Re1 e6 $1 (13... e5 14. Nd1 $1 (14. dxe6 {transposes to 13...e6.}) 14... h5 15. e4 h4 16. Qc2 Bh6 17. Bc1 $14 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gd2f3,Gd1b2,Gb2d3]}) 14. dxe6 Rxe6 {½-½ Zia,T (2261)-Gal,H (2187) Budapest FS10 IM 2024 (6)} 15. Rb1 Bb7 16. Nd5 Nc6 17. e3 {[%cal Yc6b4,Yd5f4,Gc6e5,Gc1c2] According to the engine, we have a pleasant +0.20, but visually, it seems much more than that.}) 13. bxc4 e6 (13... e5 14. Nd1 $1 {[%cal Gb2c3] In this structure, a typical yet very beautiful move.} Bg4 15. Re1 $1 ({Another possible idea is} 15. f3 $16 Bd7 16. Bc3 Bh6 $6 17. e3 {[%cal Gf3f4]} Nb7 18. Rb1 a5 {Kaasen,T (2471)-Vykouk,J (2488) Budva MNE 2023} 19. f4 $18 {[%cal Gc1b2]}) 15... Qc7 16. Bc3 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gd1e3]}) (13... Rb4 {Since our idea is to play Nd1 and Bc3, this move helps us achieve it with tempo!} 14. Nd1 $1 $16 Rb8 15. Bc3 Nd7 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Qc3+ Kg8 {Blagojevic,D (2472)-Draskovic,L (2504) Niksic MNE 2023} 18. f4 $1 $18 {[%csl Ra5,Rc8][%cal Gg3g4,Gg4g5,Gd1f2,Gh2h4] White will gradually crush Black's position with the plan g4-g5-Nf2-h4. I don't see any counterplay for Black.}) 14. Rb1 $1 Re8 15. e3 $1 (15. Ba1 $5 {1-0 (32) Indjic,A (2621)-Yuffa,D (2597) Sharjah UAE 2022} Rb4 $1 $14) 15... Ng4 {Berry,N (2260)-Kirk,E (2393) England ENG 2024} (15... e5 16. Qc2 Bd7 17. Rfc1 $1 $16 {[%cal Gc3d1]}) 16. dxe6 $1 {Now is the ideal moment to capture on e6! We can either take control of the d5 square or play Nce4. In either case, the d6 pawn will become weak, and the a1-h8 diagonal will create a serious threat to Black.} Bxe6 (16... fxe6 $2 17. Nce4 $1 {[%csl Rd6]} Ne5 18. Bxe5 $1 Rxb1 19. Qxb1 Bxe5 20. Qd3 $18 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gf1d1,Gd2f3]}) 17. Nd5 $1 {[%csl Gd5]} Ne5 (17... Bxb2 18. Rxb2 Rxb2 (18... Qd7 19. Rxb8 Rxb8 20. Qc3 $18 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gh2h3,Gd5f6,Gd2e4]}) 19. Qxb2 Ne5 20. h3 $18 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gb2a3,Gf2f4,Gd2e4,Gf1b1] White threatens so many things that it's impossible for Black to prevent all of them.}) 18. Bxe5 $1 {We remove the only dangerous Black piece and start playing over the light squares!} Rxb1 19. Qxb1 Bxe5 20. Qc2 $16 {[%cal Gf1b1,Gc2a4,Gh2h4] Qa4-Rb1 is coming, after which we will control the b-file and apply pressure on the a6 pawn. Black has the bishop pair, but it's useless in this position. According to the engine, we have +1.} *

