{[%evp 0,33,22,28,23,20,27,24,34,17,12,6,18,37,30,37,32,38,26,-72,32,21,8,21,16,35,-156,-12,-8,7,80,-13,3,39,25,0]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nc3 c6 7. O-O Bf5 8. Ng5 $5 e5 (8... h6 $5 {The second most played move by Black. We continue with the strong} 9. e4 $1 Bg4 10. Nf3 $1 (10. f3 $2 {is the most played move, but it's a mistake!} hxg5 11. fxg4 Nh7 12. Be3 Nd7 $11 {[%cal Gc6c5]}) 10... e5 (10... Qc8 $6 11. Be3 Bh3 12. Qc2 $146 (12. Qb3 {is another good option for White.} Bxg2 13. Kxg2 $16 {1-0 Ivanisevic,I (2563)-Tosic,M (2447) SCG-chT Budva 2003 (8.23)}) 12... Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Nbd7 14. a4 Qc7 15. h3 $16 {We have achieved many strategically important goals. It is now questionable what Black's plan is.}) (10... Nbd7 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 e5 13. d5 $16 c5 14. Kg2 a6 15. Rh1 Rb8 16. a4 $16 {[%csl Gd1][%cal Gf3e2,Gc1e3]}) 11. Be3 $1 $146 {[%cal Gd4d5] I’m surprised that this logical move is a novelty.} ({It's too early for} 11. d5 {since after} cxd5 12. cxd5 {Black has the strong, typical} b5 $1 $146 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gb8a6]}) 11... exd4 12. Bxd4 Re8 13. h3 $1 Be6 {Of course, Black keeps the light-squared bishop, as trading it for the knight would be a huge strategic mistake.} 14. Qe2 $1 {[%csl Gc4]} Nbd7 15. Rfd1 $1 $14 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ga1c1]}) (8... d5 {It’s not played often, but it’s definitely one of the strongest continuations for Black.} 9. h3 $1 h6 10. Nf3 dxc4 (10... Be6 $5 11. g4 $13 {[%cal Gc1f4]}) 11. g4 (11. Nh4 $5 $146 {[%cal Ge2e4]}) 11... Bc8 12. e4 b5 13. a3 $146 (13. Qc2 Na6 $132 {[%cal Ga6b4];½-½ Gaal,Z (2298)-Sliwicka,A (2254) BL 2223 (Women) Germany 2022 (10.4)}) 13... Nbd7 $1 14. Be3 Bb7 15. e5 Nh7 16. Qe2 $13 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gf2f4,Gf3h4] Objectively, the position is equal. Being a pawn up, it's logical for the engine to give such an evaluation. However, practically speaking, I think White's position is preferable, as he has more space and a healthier structure. We can continue with Rad1, followed by Nh4 and f4-f5.}) 9. d5 $1 a5 (9... h6 10. Nge4 Ne8 11. Be3 $1 ({Equally good is} 11. c5 dxc5 12. Nxc5 $16 {Kollars,D (2471)-Lubbe,M (2319) Lüneburg GER 2016}) 11... Bxe4 12. Nxe4 f5 13. Nc3 $16 {[%cal Ga1c1]}) (9... cxd5 $6 {In this position, I’ve missed my chance to take} 10. Nxd5 $1 {[%csl Rd6] As the bishop remains strong on the h1-a8 diagonal, the pawn on d6 will become a long-term weakness.} Nc6 11. Nxf6+ Bxf6 12. Ne4 $16 Be7 (12... Bxe4 $6 {A questionable decision. After this move, Black can hardly make any counterplay. We keep the bishop pair while the d6 pawn remains a weakness.} 13. Bxe4 {[%csl Gc1,Rd6,Ge4]} Qc7 14. b3 Rad8 15. Ba3 Qa5 16. Bb2 Bg7 17. Qd5 Qc7 18. Rfd1 Rd7 19. Rac1 Kh8 20. Qd2 f5 21. Bd5 $16 {Predojevic,B (2578)-Stojanovic,D (2458) Bajina Basta SRB 2023}) 13. Bh6 Re8 {Grischuk,A (2778)-Rakhmanov,A (2653) Moscow RUS 2021} 14. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gb2b3,Gd1d2,Ga1c1,Gf1d1]}) (9... Qc7 $5 10. dxc6 bxc6 11. h3 $1 $146 {Preparing g4 and Nge4.} (11. b4 h6 $6 12. Nge4 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Rd8 {Shtembuliak,E (2548)-Kadric,D (2558) Saint Louis USA 2019} 14. Be3 $1 d5 15. cxd5 cxd5 16. Rc1 Qe7 17. Bc5 Qe6 18. Nd6 $1 {[%csl Rd5]} e4 19. f3 Nc6 20. Nxf5 gxf5 21. Bh3 Rab8 22. Qd2 Bf6 $13) (11. Nb5 $2 cxb5 12. Bxa8 h6 $17 {Fridman,D (2626)-Sadhwani,R (2616) Warsaw POL 2021}) 11... Rd8 (11... h6 12. g4 Bc8 13. Nge4 Ne8 (13... Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Rd8 15. g5 h5 16. Nf6+ Bxf6 17. gxf6 Nd7 18. Qd3 Re8 19. Bg5 $14 {[%csl Gg2,Gg5][%cal Gd3g3,Ga1d1]}) 14. g5 hxg5 15. b4 $1 {[%cal Gb4b5] The idea is to play b5 and fight for the d5 square!} (15. Nxg5 f6 $13) 15... Be6 (15... g4 16. hxg4 Bxg4 17. b5 a6 18. a4 $14 {[%csl Ya8,Yb8,Rd6,Ye8][%cal Gc1a3] The d6 pawn is weak, and Ba3 is coming. White's pieces are fully mobilized, while Black's pieces remain stuck on the 8th rank.}) 16. b5 $14 {[%cal Ge4g5]}) 12. g4 Bc8 13. Nge4 (13. f4 $5 {aiming for f5, looks like an interesting try for White. However, according to the engine, Black has enough counterplay to maintain a balanced position.} Nbd7 14. f5 gxf5 15. gxf5 Rb8 16. Qe1 d5 17. Qh4 Nf8 18. e4 Rb4 $1 $132) 13... Ne8 14. b4 Be6 15. Qb3 $14 {[%cal Gb4b5,Gg4g5,Ga2a4] We have a highly active position with a clear plan in mind. b5 and g5 are coming, gradually improving our position. Meanwhile, Black must find a way to generate counterplay.}) 10. Nge4 $1 (10. e4 Bc8 $1 11. h3 cxd5 12. cxd5 Na6 13. Be3 Bd7 14. a4 Rc8 $132 {Lenderman,A (2607)-Caruana,F (2800) Saint Louis USA 2021}) 10... Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Bh3 12. Bg2 Bxg2 (12... Bf5 13. dxc6 bxc6 14. Be3 Be6 15. Qa4 f5 16. Rfd1 Qc7 17. Qa3 $16 {[%csl Rd6] Moradiabadi,E (2511)-Chen,R (2374) Las Vegas USA 2024}) (12... Qd7 13. Bxh3 Qxh3 14. f3 Qd7 15. Be3 f5 16. Qb3 $14 {[%cal Ga1d1,Yc6c5,Ye3d2,Ye2e4] /}) 13. Kxg2 f5 14. Be3 {We take an active diagonal and also provoke ...f4, allowing us to take control of the e4 square.} f4 (14... Rf7 15. Qc2 Nd7 16. Rad1 Nf6 17. f3 $14) 15. Bd2 {[%csl Ge4]} Nd7 16. f3 Nf6 17. Rc1 $14 {[%cal Gd1c2,Gc3e4,Yb2b3,Ya2a3,Yb3b4] We will continue with Qc2 and Ne4, after which we will slowly prepare b4. Black might attempt counterplay on the kingside with ..Qd7 and ..g5, but we can always respond with g4 or Rg1 and Kh1.} *

