{[%evp 0,29,33,13,14,18,29,30,29,4,34,36,38,19,38,29,38,54,63,52,45,34,35,50,53,42,33,32,41,84,47,50]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 d6 5. Bg2 c6 6. Nc3 Bf5 7. O-O (7. Ng5 $5 h6 8. e4 {is a good alternative line.}) 7... Ne4 (7... O-O 8. Ng5 {transpose}) (7... Qc8 $5 {[%cal Gf5h3]} 8. Re1 {[%cal Ge2e4]} Ne4 (8... Bh3 {doesn't make sense here, as e4-e5 can no longer be stopped.} 9. e4 Bxg2 10. Kxg2 Na6 (10... Nfd7 11. h4 $1 $146 {[%cal Gh4h5]} h5 12. Bg5 $18 {[%csl Ra8,Rb8,Rc8,Re8][%cal Ge4e5]}) 11. e5 $16 {[%cal Ge5e6]}) {Here, I suggest the interesting novelty, with the same idea as in the main line} 9. Na4 $1 $146 {[%cal Gf3h4] avoiding the exchange while introducing the immediate threat of Nh4.} ({Another interesting alternative could be} 9. h4 $5 h6 10. Bf4 $14) 9... Nf6 (9... Bh3 10. Qd3 Bf5 (10... Nf6 11. e4 $16 {[%cal Ge4e5]}) 11. Qe3 Nf6 12. Qa3 $1 {[%cal Ga4b6] Such a beautiful move! It threats Nb6 while simultaneously repositioning the queen to enable Nc3-e4.} Nbd7 13. Nc3 {[%cal Gf3h4,Ge2e4]} O-O 14. Nh4 {[%csl Rf5]} Nb6 15. Nxf5 gxf5 16. Qb3 $14 {[%csl Gc1,Gg2][%cal Gd4d5] /. Black is now without his light-squared bishop and also has doubled pawns. With d5 coming, we have a strategically dominant position.}) 10. Qb3 O-O 11. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4]} Nbd7 (11... Ne4 $2 12. g4 $1 $16 {[%csl Re4,Rf5]}) 12. e4 Bg4 13. Qc2 e5 14. d5 cxd5 15. cxd5 Nc5 16. a4 {[%cal Gf3d2] Since we are playing on the queenside, with cxd5 included, White's play is much easier. Nd2-Nc4 is coming, and we have a pleasant position. According to the engine, the evaluation is +0.50.}) 8. Na4 $5 {[%cal Gf3h4] Played only a few times, I really like the concept of this move. We simply avoid the knight exchange, waiting for the right moment to return to c3 and push e4.} (8. h4 $5 $146 {} Nxc3 9. bxc3 Nd7 10. h5 Qa5 (10... gxh5 11. Nh4 Bg6 12. e4 Bf6 13. Re1 Bxh4 14. gxh4 Qc7 {[%cal Ge8c8]} 15. Bf4 e5 16. Bg3 $14 {[%csl Gg2,Gg3,Rg6][%cal Ga2a4]}) 11. h6 Bf6 12. Qb3 $14 {[%csl Gh6]}) 8... Nf6 ({Obviously,} 8... O-O $6 {would be a mistake, as we can play 9.Nh4, capturing the light-squared bishop and gaining a positional advantage.} 9. Nh4 $1 {[%csl Re4,Rf5]} d5 10. Nxf5 gxf5 11. Qb3 $1 Qd7 12. Nc3 e6 13. Rd1 Nd6 (13... b5 14. c5 $1 a5 15. Bf4 $16 {[%cal Gf2f3]}) 14. c5 $1 Nc8 $5 {[%cal Gb7b6]} (14... Ne4 15. Bf4 $16 {[%cal Gf2f3]}) 15. Bf4 b6 16. Na4 b5 17. Nc3 a5 18. Qc2 $1 $14 {[%cal Ge2e3,Gc3e2,Ge2c1,Gc1d3] /}) 9. Qb3 $5 {Since 9.Nh4 would transpose to Chapter 1, I suggest another move, but with the same idea – to push e4.} (9. Nh4 Bc8 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Nf3 Nbd7 12. e4 e5 {1-0 Lazavik,D (2567)-Bacrot,E (2680) Titled Tuesday intern op 26th Mar Early Chess.com INT blitz 2024 (4)} 13. Qc2 {transposes to Chapter 1.}) 9... Qc7 {½-½ Gurevich,D (2505)-Benjamin,J (2595) USA-ch sf Denver 1998 (1)} 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Re1 {[%cal Ge2e4]} e5 (11... Ne4 $4 12. g4 $1 Nxc3 13. gxf5 Ne4 14. Nh4 Nf6 15. c5 $1 $18 {[%cal Gf5g6,Yg8h8,Yb3h3]}) 12. e4 Bg4 {Here, we have two good options to choose from, depending on our style and which structure we prefer more.} 13. Be3 (13. d5 $14) 13... Bxf3 14. Bxf3 exd4 15. Bxd4 $14 *

