{[%evp 0,45,11,-10,5,11,37,26,33,12,11,7,19,32,43,39,55,12,40,42,37,22,0,25,33,-45,34,38,-123,28,65,17,-101,-52,-147,0,41,-11,-182,-85,-214,9,-20,-23,38,-2,-71,-3]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nc3 c6 7. O-O Qa5 8. Bd2 (8. Qd2 $5 {[%cal Ya5h5,Yd2g5] can be an interesting alternative to 9.Bd2. The idea is very simple: the moment Black plays ...Qh5, we will play Qg5, trading queens and playing a slightly better position on the structure.}) 8... Qh5 {[%cal Gc8h3]} (8... Qa6 9. b3 d5 ({A much weaker move would be} 9... b5 $6 {as it allows us to easily open the queenside, supported by the strong bishop on g2.} 10. cxb5 cxb5 11. a4 $1 {[%csl Gg2]} b4 (11... bxa4 $2 12. Rxa4 Qb6 13. Ne5 Bb7 14. Nc4 Qc7 15. e4 $1 $18 {[%cal Gc4a5,Gc3b5]}) 12. Nb5 Qb6 13. Ne5 $1 $146 ({There’s nothing wrong with taking a free pawn.} 13. Bxb4 $14) 13... dxe5 (13... Bb7 $4 14. Nc4 $18 {[%cal Gb6a6,Gb5c7]}) 14. Bxa8 a6 15. dxe5 $1 Ng4 16. h3 $1 Nxe5 17. Be3 Qa5 18. Nd4 Bxh3 19. Bg2 $16 {We have a material advantage; the rest should be just pure technique.}) 10. cxd5 $1 (10. Rc1 $5 $14) 10... cxd5 11. b4 $1 Bf5 12. Qb3 Qd6 13. b5 $1 (13. Bf4 Qb6 14. Na4 Qb5 $14 {[%csl Gb5]}) 13... e6 $1 (13... Ne4 $6 14. Bf4 Qd8 {1-0 Radjabov,T (2758)-Ziska,H (2533) FIDE World Cup Khanty-Mansiysk 2019 (1.1)} 15. Rac1 $1 $18 {[%cal Gc3e4,Gf4c7,Gc7a5]}) 14. h3 h5 15. Bf4 Qe7 16. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5,Gf1c1,Gf3e5]}) 9. h4 $5 {[%cal Gf3h2,Gg2f3] A rare but interesting move. The idea is to play Nh2 and Bf3, removing the queen and any potential attack on the kingside.} ({Also, a good alternative for White could be.} 9. Qb3 e5 (9... Na6 10. h3 $1 $16) (9... b6 10. h4 $1 $16) 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Ng5 $16) 9... h6 (9... e5 10. d5 {[%csl Rh5]} Qg4 $5 {Brandhorst,D-Hausrath,D (2454) Essen 2003} 11. dxc6 $1 Nxc6 12. b3 Qd7 13. Rc1 $1 {[%csl Rd6]} h6 {It's necessary for Black to prevent Bg5.} (13... Rb8 $6 14. Bg5 $1 h6 (14... Ng4 15. Rc2 $16 {[%cal Gc2d2]}) 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Qd5 $16 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gf1d1,Gf3d2,Gd2e4] Rfd1 followed by Nd2-e4 is coming, increasing pressure on the d6 weakness while taking full advantage of the light squares.}) 14. e4 $1 Qd8 15. Nh2 Be6 16. Be3 Kh7 17. Qd2 $16 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gf1d1,Gc3b5]}) (9... Nbd7 10. e4 e5 11. d5 h6 12. Qc2 Ng4 {[%cal Gf7f5]} 13. Rad1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd5c6,Gd2c1]} f5 14. dxc6 bxc6 15. Bc1 Rf6 16. exf5 gxf5 17. Ne1 {[%cal Gf2f3]} e4 18. f3 exf3 19. Nxf3 $16 {[%csl Yc6,Yd6,Yf5][%cal Gf3d4] I believe we can stop here. There is no attack from Black, while his structure remains completely disrupted.}) 10. Rc1 Na6 11. Nh2 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Gg2f3]} g5 $1 {Black is trying to find a safe square for his queen on g6.} (11... e5 {This natural move fails for Black because after} 12. d5 cxd5 13. Nxd5 $1 Nxd5 {White simply captures with} 14. Bxd5 $16 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gb2b4,Ge2e4] where Black is left without counterplay, and the pawn on d6 becomes a lasting weakness.}) 12. Bf3 Qg6 13. e4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] Now, h5 becomes a powerful threat, as the queen would be forced to retreat to the passive square h7.} gxh4 (13... e5 $6 {In this line, we will see why allowing h5 is so dangerous.} 14. h5 $1 Qh7 {[%csl Rh7]} 15. d5 {[%csl Rh7]} cxd5 (15... Nc5 16. dxc6 bxc6 17. b4 Ne6 18. Be3 Bb7 19. Bg2 Rfe8 20. Re1 Nd4 21. b5 c5 22. a4 $16 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Ga4a5,Ge3d2,Gh2g4]}) 16. Nxd5 $1 {Absolutely, we capture with the knight. Now, it's not possible for Black to play ...Nc5 with tempo on the e4 pawn, followed by ...a5.} Nxd5 17. cxd5 f5 (17... Nc5 18. Bb4 $1 b6 19. Bxc5 $1 bxc5 20. b4 cxb4 21. Rc6 $18 {[%csl Rd6,Rh7][%cal Gf3g4]}) 18. b4 $1 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Rh7][%cal Gd1e2,Ga2a4] Our next few moves will be Qe2 followed by b4, gradually squeezing on the queenside. There is no counterplay on the kingside, as after every ...f4, we can always trade light-squared bishops on g4, effectively neutralizing any attack. And of course, the queen on h7 is completely passive and ineffective.}) 14. Kh1 $1 {[%cal Gf1g1] Preparing Rg1!} h3 (14... hxg3 {Opening the g-file definitely favors us!} 15. Rg1 gxh2 16. Rxg6 fxg6 17. Be2 $16 {[%cal Gd2e3,Gh1h2] I don't believe in Black's compensation.}) 15. g4 $1 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gf1g1] A deadly move for Black! We're simply preparing Rg1-g5.} (15. e5 {is an okay move, but perhaps a little too soon to be played, since after} Nh7 16. Be4 f5 (16... Bf5 17. Bxf5 Qxf5 18. exd6 exd6 19. Nf3 $14 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gd2e3,Gf3h4] /}) 17. Bb1 (17. exf6 Qxf6 18. Be3 Bf5 19. g4 Bxe4+ 20. Nxe4 Qg6 21. Ng3 $14) 17... dxe5 18. dxe5 Bxe5 19. Rg1 Qg7 20. Qe2 $14 {White keeps the advantage, but it will be a little bit harder to execute g4.}) 15... e5 16. Rg1 Nh7 {[%cal Rg4g5] Fighting against g5.} ({There’s no time for} 16... exd4 $2 {since after} 17. g5 $1 hxg5 18. Rxg5 Qh6 19. Rg3 Qh4 20. Bg5 $18 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gg5f6] Black can't defend both the queen and the knight on f6 at the same time.}) 17. d5 $1 {The perfect moment for d5. After this move, we close the center and eliminate any possible counterplay from Black. It's time to transfer our pieces to the kingside and aim for key squares like f5 or h5.} Bf6 18. Be2 (18. g5 {is an okay move, but I think we can achieve much more with 18.Be2.} Bxg5 19. Bh5 Qf6 20. Bxg5 hxg5 (20... Nxg5 21. f4 exf4 22. Qd2 Nc5 23. Rcf1 Qg7 24. Rxf4 f6 25. Ne2 $14 {[%cal Ge2d4,Gh5g4]}) 21. Bg4 $14 {[%cal Gg1g3,Gh2f3]}) 18... Nc5 19. f3 a5 20. Rg3 Bg5 21. Rxh3 Bf4 22. Qc2 Ng5 23. Rh5 $16 {[%cal Gc1g1,Gc2c1] Once we play Rg1 and Qc1, we will remove the bishop from the f4 square. After that, Nf1-Ne3 will prepare to target the f5 square, while keeping an eye on the c4 and d5 squares if the center structure changes.} *

