{[%evp 0,14,25,26,18,-17,37,37,33,3,-3,13,29,27,48,30,62]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nc3 c6 7. O-O Qb6 {Challenges White’s queenside while preparing counterplay against the center. It also pressures b2 and discourages White's queenside expansion, making it a flexible move with dynamic potential.} 8. c5 $1 {is a strong positional move that seizes queenside space, restricts Black's queenside play, and disrupts his coordination. It neutralizes the pressure on b2, forces awkward piece placement, and shifts the initiative firmly to White.} (8. h3 Qa6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 9. b3 b5 $13) 8... dxc5 9. Na4 Qb5 {Forces White to deal with the threat to the knight on a4 and the pawn on c5, while maintaining counterplay. However, it leaves the queen somewhat exposed and vulnerable, particularly in the future after Re1-Bf1-e4.} (9... Qd8 10. Nxc5 Nbd7 11. Nd3 $1 {I like this move very much. There’s no need to trade our good knight for his 'bad' one. At some point, Black will likely move his knight from d7 to develop his light-squared bishop, which could give us the opportunity to jump with Nde5, keeping the f3 knight for potential Ng5 ideas.} a5 (11... Nb6 12. Re1 $1 {[%cal Ge2e4]} Bg4 13. Nde5 {[%cal Yf3g5]} Bf5 (13... Bxf3 14. Nxf3 $16) 14. Ng5 $1 {[%cal Ge2e4]} Ng4 15. e4 $1 Nxe5 16. exf5 Ned7 (16... h6 $2 17. Nh3 Nec4 18. fxg6 fxg6 {Greenfeld,A (2455)-Vedrickas,T (2329) Durres ALB 2023} 19. Nf4 Qxd4 20. Qc2 $18 {[%cal Gf4e6,Gf4g6]}) 17. Bh3 Nd5 18. Qc2 $16 {[%cal Gc1d2,Ga1d1]}) 12. a4 Nb8 {[%cal Gc8f5]} 13. Bd2 Ne4 (13... Bf5 14. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Rb7]} Ne4 15. Bf4 Nd6 16. Nc5 Na6 17. Ne5 $16 {[%csl Gb3,Gc5,Ge5,Gg2] Two knights in the center, the queen exerting pressure on b7, and a strong bishop on g2 clearly secure us a dominant position.}) 14. Be1 Bf5 15. Rc1 Nd6 16. Bc3 Ne4 17. e3) 10. Nxc5 Na6 11. a4 {With the idea of 12.a5, gains control over the queenside, paralyzing Black’s structure and leaving the queen on the awkward a6-square.} Qb6 12. a5 Qb5 13. Nxa6 Qxa6 {[%csl Ga5,Ra6,Ya7,Yb7,Yc6] So, we implement our plan. We disrupt Black's coordination, with the pawn on a5 perfectly placed as it 'traps' the queen on a6, while also taking control of Black's queenside structure. Now it's time for} 14. Re1 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gg2f1] preparing to seize control of the center with e4, while also threatening Bf1.} Bf5 {Black is trying to take control of the e4 square.} (14... Rd8 $6 {[%cal Gc6c5,Gc8g4] With the idea to apply some pressure on the d4 pawn.} 15. e4 Bg4 (15... c5 $2 {Looks logical, but it's already a mistake. We have a few good moves to decline this idea.} 16. e5 $1 Ne8 17. Bg5 $1 $146 {[%csl Re7]} (17. Qa4 $1 b5 {Blagojevic,D (2514)-Dimic,P (2034) Obrenovac 2011} 18. Qa3 $1 b4 19. Qe3 $16) 17... Bf8 (17... Bg4 18. Bxe7 Rxd4 19. Qc1 Bxf3 20. Bxf3 Rc8 21. Bg5 $18 {[%csl Gf3,Gg5][%cal Gg5e3] The bishop pair is too strong here. Black's g7-bishop is closed, the knight on e8 is out of the game, and the queen is tied to b7. We have a decisive advantage.}) 18. Be3 (18. d5 $5 {is also a winning move, but it requires us to trade the queen for a rook and bishop.} Be6 19. dxe6 Rxd1 20. exf7+ Kxf7 21. Rexd1 Nc7 22. Be3 $18 {[%cal Gd1c1,Gb2b4]}) 18... Bg4 19. Qa4 Bd7 20. Qc2 Bf5 21. Qc3 $1 {[%csl Ra6,Ye8,Yf8][%cal Ge1c1,Gg2f1,Gd4c5] All of Black's pieces are tied, while we have an active position. According to the engine, we have a "pleasant" +1.50 advantage.}) 16. Qb3 $1 (16. Qa4 {Markus,R (2609)-Jankovic,A (2558) Bol 2014} Nd7 $1 17. Be3 $14) 16... Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Rxd4 18. Be3 Rd3 19. Qc2 {[%cal Gf3e2]} c5 20. Qxc5 $1 (20. Be2 c4 21. Bxd3 cxd3 22. Qb3 $16) 20... Nd7 21. Qc2 {[%cal Gf3e2]} Rd6 22. Be2 Qc6 23. Qxc6 Rxc6 24. Rac1 Rac8 25. Rxc6 Rxc6 26. Bb5 Rc7 27. Rd1 Nf8 28. Bxa7 Bxb2 29. Rd8 $16 {[%csl Ga7,Gb5,Rb7][%cal Ga7b6] /+-}) (14... Be6 $6 {doesn't seem threatening, as we immediately seize the center with} 15. e4 Rad8 (15... Rfd8 16. Ng5 $1 c5 17. Nxe6 Qxe6 18. d5 Qa6 19. Bg5 h6 20. Bf1 Qd6 21. Bf4 e5 22. Bd2 $16 {[%csl Gd2,Gf1][%cal Gd1a4,Ga5a6]}) 16. Bf4 Qb5 17. Qc2 $16 {[%csl Ga5,Ya7,Yb7,Yc6,Gd4,Ge4]}) 15. Ng5 $1 {[%cal Ge2e4]} h6 16. e4 Bg4 17. f3 Bd7 (17... Bc8 18. Nh3 $16 {[%cal Gg2f1]}) 18. Bf1 b5 19. Nh3 {[%cal Gh3f4,Yf4d3,Yd3c5]} Bxh3 {Since we threat to transfer the knight to the powerful c5 square, this is likely Black’s best response.} (19... Rfd8 20. Nf4 Be8 21. e5 Nd5 22. Nd3 $16 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gd3c5]}) (19... c5 20. dxc5 Rad8 21. Nf4 Be6 22. Qc2 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Gc5]}) 20. Bxh3 Rfd8 21. f4 $1 {[%csl Ra6,Gd4,Ge4,Gf4]} e6 22. b4 $1 {[%csl Ra6]} Qb7 23. Qd3 $1 Rac8 24. Bg2 $14 {[%cal Ge1d1,Gc1b2,Gd3b3] Conclusion: Black's position is playable, but requires deep theoretical knowledge to avoid being consistently much worse. It could serve as an interesting surprise, but nothing more than that.} *

