14... b5 15. c5 $1 {It’s a basic element of White's strategy in the Fianchetto KID. When executed under the right circumstances, it removes the d6 pawn, activates the pawn structure with f4-e5, opens the light-squared bishop, and leaves Black's queenside weakened.} dxc5 16. Bxe5 cxd4 (16... Qxe5 $2 {allows us to open the position with} 17. Nxc6 {leading to an endgame with a pawn up and a decisive advantage.} Qc7 18. e5 $1 Bf5 19. Qc1 b4 20. exf6 bxc3 21. Qxc3 Be4 22. Qxc5 Bxf6 23. Rac1 Bxg2 24. Kxg2 $18 {[%cal Gc5d5,Gd5d7]}) 17. Bxd4 Bb7 ({One of the top KID experts played} 17... Be6 $6 {Liu,Y (2476)-Kotronias,V (2529) Moscow RUS 2018} {here, but I propose} 18. Ne2 $1 Rad8 19. Rac1 $16 {[%csl Ya6,Yb5,Yc6][%cal Gd4c5,Gf2f4] where Black's queenside weakness is clear. Meanwhile, we also threat Bc5 and f4.}) 18. Rac1 $1 {[%csl Ga5,Gb6,Yb7,Gc5] We are fighting for control of all the dark squares.} *

