{[%evp 0,35,19,32,15,-41,35,25,29,10,49,13,20,33,34,41,46,34,46,19,58,93,68,56,72,58,64,65,57,41,56,54,56,73,66,50,44,50]} {Black just played} 10... Bb7 $6 {before ...exd4. How can we punish that?} 11. d5 $1 {Now, with Bb7 and Rfe8 played, it's the right moment for this move. The bishop remains restricted on b7, while the rook on e8 can't support the ...f7-f5 idea.} a5 {[%cal Gd7c5]} 12. Be3 {[%cal Rf6g4] Here we can see the benefit of 9.h3.} Nc5 13. Rfe1 {[%csl Ge4] It can be useful to defend the e4 pawn in the future.} Bc8 {[%cal Gc8d7] It's time to bring the bishop back to life, as on b7 it doesn't do anything useful.} 14. a3 $1 {We usually start with b3, then a3, slowly preparing b4. But here, 14...a4 is not possible, as we can simply capture the knight on c5 and the pawn on a4.} Bd7 (14... a4 $6 {[%csl Ya3,Ga4,Yb2]} 15. Bxc5 bxc5 16. Nxa4 $16 {[%csl Ge1,Ge4]}) 15. b4 $16 {Strategically speaking, I think White has a dominant position. Black hasn't initiated any play on the kingside, while we have already made significant progress on the queenside.} *

