{[%evp 0,45,20,25,23,22,33,29,29,19,16,11,31,29,33,31,56,43,-13,41,38,-84,47,-24,25,42,37,44,-86,39,38,-51,-78,0,-137,2,25,-12,-171,14,-213,7,38,-130,42,-16,-104,-10]} {Black just ignored all our threats with} 13... e5 $6 {How should we punish this?} 14. h5 $1 Qh7 {[%csl Rh7]} 15. d5 {[%csl Rh7]} cxd5 (15... Nc5 16. dxc6 bxc6 17. b4 Ne6 18. Be3 Bb7 19. Bg2 Rfe8 20. Re1 Nd4 21. b5 c5 22. a4 $16 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Ga4a5,Ge3d2,Gh2g4]}) 16. Nxd5 $1 {Absolutely, we capture with the knight. Now, it's not possible for Black to play ...Nc5 with tempo on the e4 pawn, followed by ...a5.} Nxd5 17. cxd5 f5 (17... Nc5 18. Bb4 $1 b6 19. Bxc5 $1 bxc5 20. b4 cxb4 21. Rc6 $18 {[%csl Rd6,Rh7][%cal Gf3g4]}) 18. b4 $1 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Rh7][%cal Gd1e2,Ga2a4] Our next few moves will be Qe2 followed by b4, gradually squeezing on the queenside. There is no counterplay on the kingside, as after every ...f4, we can always trade light-squared bishops on g4, effectively neutralizing any attack. And of course, the queen on h7 is completely passive and ineffective.} *

